; font-size:11pt">as part of a go</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">verning body’s preparations for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">conversion –</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> it was certainly the case that some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">early converters</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> did not pay enough attention to governance requirements of becoming an academy.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  Secondly, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as stated above, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">there has been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">little attention paid to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">suppor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t the high-performing converter has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to provide to another school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">whose name is declared on the application form</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In all the schools where there has been a serious failure, whether that is financial, performance standards or management, poor gover</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nance has been instrumental.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Although this is also the case in failing LA maintained schools, the risks are greater with academies due to greater autonomy provided by the legal structures. G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overnance arrangements are particularly important in relation to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the approval of new free schools and academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.   I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">absolutely </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">essential that the body (i.e. academy trust) accountable for running the school has the skills and capabilities to do so.  While it is impossible to elim</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ate any element of risk from such</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> enterprises</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> more scrutiny at an early stage w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uld flag up potential risk factors</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">strategies could be put in place to mitigate those risks.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  Free schools pose particular challenges</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as it is can </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be difficult for founders who have been involved in almo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">st all activities during a start-up phase to be adopt a strategic governance role</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is perhaps better </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">understood in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">broader </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">charitable sector</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> where this is not an unusual situation.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Likewise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> it appears that some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">multi-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">academy trusts </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(MATs) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have been allowed to expand too rapidly with no thought for their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">governance and other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">capacity to continue t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o function effectively.   The DfE’s policy imperative to encourage or compel more schools to become academies appears to have led to some academy t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rusts taking on more schools than they can realistically improve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> at one time</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  The problem for academy sponsors is that the schools they are asked to take </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">over </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">inevitably have significant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">performance issues, including management and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">teaching quality issues</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This means that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">trust </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that expands too quickly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a few schools wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ich are good or outstanding but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a majority which require </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">significant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> support.  Providing that support to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a small number of under-performing schools may be possible, whereas </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">looking a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 20 or more in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">disparate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> geographical </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">locations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is a much more challenging prospect.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The process for compelling under-performing schools to become sponsored academies could be improved.   In particular discussions between DfE brokers and governing bodies should be documented, not necessarily in full, but in sufficient detail to prevent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">putes later in the process. We receive some reports where governing bodies claim to have bee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n told incorrect information by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> brokers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or potential sponsors, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">but there is no way of determining this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as all the conversations have taken place without any records</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  There also needs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to be information from the DfE in each case laying out </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">when the DfE can and will intervene to impose a sponsor as opposed to convincing an unwilling governing body that they have no other option than choosing a sponsor.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A few gov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">erning bodies have reported after joining a sponsored chain that the delegation or other arrangements were different from what they expected; however there is no documentation setting out the details until after the decision has been made. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">NGA advises gove</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rnors in this situation to look at the small print, but often they have not asked the right questions at the point of making a decision about a sponsor. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Decisions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> about who should take over an underperforming school need to take into consideration the sponsor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s capacity to do a good job – an impact assessment should be carried out on the likely effects on the existing schools under the sponsor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s control, not simply</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> their track record to date.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  This is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">similar </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to when making an admission decision and considering whether admitting a particular pupil would ‘prejudice the efficient education’ for the other pupils.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  The impact assessment should consider a range of organi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sational aspects, including back office functions, leadership capacity, school improvement expertise, and governance structures and personnel.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The willingness of the MAT to take on another school must be a prerequisite. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are also aware that some high </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">performing schools that have taken </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on one under-performing school </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are being put under pressure by DfE brokers to take on a second </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">challenging </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">school, even where the MAT board has made a decision that it does not have the capacity to do this at present.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NGA understands</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfE’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">policy imperative for free schools is not the provision of school places in areas of greatest need, but the NGA remains concerned that a number, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">particularly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">secondary free schools, have been established where there is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> no need at all for new school places and the schools in the surrounding area are not underperforming. This cannot be a good use of public money at a time of such financial austerity.</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The role of the Secretary of State in intervening in and supporting fa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">iling academies and how this role will work as the programme expands</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Given that local authorities can find it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">difficult </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to monitor the schools in their</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> local</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> areas it was always going to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">challenging, if not impossible for the DfE to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">effectively</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> monitor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the number of academies from Westminster.  The DfE has recently announced the recruitme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nt of Regional Commissioners to run </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">elected ‘headteacher boards’. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">NGA understands that there is a need for a change of structure to monitor the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">performance of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">thousands of academies across England and to intervene when they, governed by their board of trustees, are not performing well. It is not tenable for the Secretary of State, or even civil servants in Whitehall to undertake this scrutiny and intervention fu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nction on his behalf.  The Commissioners' </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">responsibilities will include:  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">monitoring the performance of academies; intervening to secure improvement in underperforming academies; approving applications to convert to academy status;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">monitoring the performan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ce of academy sponsors; and authorising new sponsors.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Given that the role includes monitoring the performance of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">academy trusts and their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sponsors and authorising new sponsors the NGA is disappointed that governance expertise is not being included on thes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e boards.  The NGA’s view is that given the remit such boards would need members with a wider range of skills and experiences than headteacher only boards.  In our view the proposed name and make-up of these boards does not seem to recognise that the respo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nsibility for school standards rests with the accountable body, which is the academy trust – this is a governance function.  If standards in an academy are falling then governance is likely to be an issue – it is, therefore, a mistake in our view that ther</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e will be no governance expertise included in these boards</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are also concerned </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that election to these boards </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is unlikely to be a robust method of ensuring the best qualified and skilled board members.  W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e know already from the experience of schools foru</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ms that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> obtaining input from academies, that do not necessary have local forums </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to consul</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">each other, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">can be difficult.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Using</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> election is unexpected from a G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overnment that has been promoting the appointment of governors and trustees as the best way to en</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sure the right skills are on the Governing Board</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of schools.   </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The functions and responsibilities in relation to academies and free schools of local authorities and other organisations operating between the SofS and individual schools; what these funct</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ion should be and what gaps there are in support for schools at this level</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">currently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">very practical difficulties for local authorities in exercising any over-sight of academies. Local authorities have no powers to intervene in academies and apart from the published national data, not necessarily and insight into what is happening inside th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e academy.  Where local authorities do have local intelligence then this should be reported to the Education </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Funding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Agency or potentially in future the Regional </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Commissioner</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  Local authorities could opt to use their scrutiny processes, but this is not co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mmon practice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and as their own capacity diminishes it is unlikely to become more so.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While some academies are very well networked and leading or engaged with such initiatives as Teaching School alliances, others are not involved in collaborative ventures.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  Some providers of school improvement services can be expensive and not quality assured.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What role academy chains play or should play in the new school landscape; how accountable they are; and what issues they raise with regard to governance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">arrangements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Academy chains are as different as individual academies and all operate slightly differently.  It has become apparent that some chains have not given sufficient thought to how to lead and manage the academies within their trust as they grow </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bigger.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The way in which governance and management is conducted needs to be very different in a chain with five schools compared to a chain of 20, 30 or 70 schools.  It is simply not possible for a single board of directors to give the same level of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">scrut</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iny</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to 70 schools compared with five</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  The Academy Trust’s scheme of delegation and control needs to change to fit the size of the organisation – in a number of cases this does not appear to have been managed effectively.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is no current research to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">indica</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">te </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">how big is too big – and indeed size may not be the limiting factor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, as intermediates board could be interposed between the overarching board and each small group of academies.   Governance capacity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> skills, and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> structure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">key, but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the anec</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dotal evidence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">this is often </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not being done well currently.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is also the case that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">smaller</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> chains are coming into existence as the DfE </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">encourages standalone</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> converter academies to take over under-performing schools.   </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">NGA’s research into local a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uthority federat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ions shows that these work well when</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ethos, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vision</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and strategy is shared, and there are advantages to having local members of the group.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The appropriateness of academy status for primary schools and what special factors apply; and wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">at evidence there is that academy  status can bring value for money either for individual primary schools or for the system as a whole.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We see the biggest barrier</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">many primary schools converting is the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lack of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">staff capacity to take on the additional </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">responsibilities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (particularly in relation to finance) of academy status.  The NGA thinks that access to a good business manager is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> essential</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to taking on academy status and many primary schools still do not employ someone in such a role.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">By definition mo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">st primary schools have smaller budgets and consequently less purchasing power than secondary schools and while it is true that purchasing some items at a local level can bring cost benefits, generally speaking economies of scale offer greater value for mo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ney</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for small schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> LA maintained federation can provide primary schools with the advantages of scal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e, i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">terms of development and career progression for staff, opportunities for children, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">procurement and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">more effective governance, all adding up to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> improved outcomes for children</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">without the need for as much backroom change dictated by the new legal framework as opposed to first and foremost the priorities of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pupils of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">school.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What alternatives to sponsored academy status should be offered</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> to primary schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NGA thinks that in any situation where a school is causing concern the solution put in place should be the best one </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">available</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  While there is no doubt that for some schools sponsored conversion to academy status has been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">effective, it is also true that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">schools under local authority control have made a rapid journey from special measures to good or better.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  There are increasing numbers of examples where improvement is already underway by the time a school is forcibly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">taken over by an academy sponsor.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">When teaching need</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to be improved</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in a school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">structural change to a different legal framework may not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be the most important priority.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NGA is concerned, and this has been noted by Ofsted inspectors in reports, tha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t in some cases the workload and bureaucracy involved in the sponsor conversion can actually divert schools’ attention away from the critical issue of school improvement.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This cannot be in the best interests of children and young people.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial;